<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="41.[264,1326,283,1870]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,427,1443,1469]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Variation</emphasis>
. The pile on the body varies from white to golden yellow and the tomentum varies from yellow to golden yellow. Some specimens have the hair on the basal antennal segments and the ocellar tubercle white instead of black. The mid and hind tibiae are often brownish. In the female vaginal furca there often is a small translucent swelling on the arms of the lower half.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="41.[264,1326,283,1870]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,444,1643,1669]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Discussion</emphasis>
. The long projection on the venter of the gonocoxa is a reliable means of recognizing 
<taxonomicName box="[410,542,1684,1709]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigripes">
<emphasis box="[410,542,1684,1709]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">G. nigripes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This projection is longer and more easily seen, even in the rosette condition, than in the other species, which possess a projection. A comparison of the male genitalia of both 
<taxonomicName box="[463,595,1764,1789]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigripes">
<emphasis box="[463,595,1764,1789]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">G. nigripes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[652,794,1764,1789]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="winburni">
<emphasis box="[652,794,1764,1789]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">G. winburni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
supports the synonymy of the two species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="41.[264,1326,283,1870]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,404,1803,1829]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Biology</emphasis>
. Nothing is known of the immatures. Adults have been taken at flowers of 
<taxonomicName box="[264,553,1844,1869]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Eriogonum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Polygonales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fasciculatum">
<emphasis box="[264,553,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Eriogonum fasciculatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[568,666,1844,1869]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Achillea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[568,666,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Achillea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp., and 
<taxonomicName box="[770,1029,1844,1869]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Tetradymia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="canescens">
<emphasis box="[770,1029,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Tetradymia canescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
